About the use case. Here is a question about class based properties with 25 up-votes: http://stackoverflow.com/questions/5189699/how-can-i-make-a-class-property-in-python
OK, this only show interest, but no real use case ...

Here is our use case. We use django ORM to access PostgreSQL.

We have model "Foo" which is of a particular type. The types are stored in the model "FooType". There is a default type, and this can be accessed with `FooType.default`

```
class FooType(models.Model):
   # ...
    @classproperty
    def default(cls):
        return cls.objects.get(slug=cls.SLUG_DEFAULT)


```

Of course `FooType.get_default()` would work, too. But `FooType.default` is easier according to my point of view.

